---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout current="beliefs" title="Beliefs — Dushyant Garg">
  <div class="container">
    <section class="page-intro">
      <h1 class="page-title reveal">Beliefs<span class="dot">.</span></h1>
    </section>

    <section class="section-stack beliefs-content">
      <article class="belief-block reveal" style="--reveal-delay: 0.05s;">
        <h2>MAP over motivation</h2>
        <p>
          MAP is my execution loop: <strong>Map the work</strong>, <strong>Act in small loops</strong>,
          <strong>Publish results early</strong>. Plans are only useful when they reduce decision load.
          If a project feels fuzzy, I make the next action unmissable.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="belief-block reveal" style="--reveal-delay: 0.1s;">
        <h2>Taste in AI means constraints</h2>
        <p>
          Good AI products feel opinionated. I optimize for tools that are legible, auditable,
          and actually useful at 2 AM. If an agent cannot explain what it changed, it has not
          earned trust yet.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="belief-block reveal" style="--reveal-delay: 0.15s;">
        <h2>One-ticket, one-turn</h2>
        <p>
          I prefer narrow tickets with hard acceptance criteria. One clean turn beats five half-fixes.
          Ship small, verify, commit, repeat. Speed is real only when quality survives contact.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="belief-block reveal" style="--reveal-delay: 0.2s;">
        <h2>Build for the next tired version of yourself</h2>
        <p>
          Most systems break when context disappears. I design workflows for handoff: clear names,
          searchable logs, and defaults that make the right path obvious. Future me should be able
          to resume instantly.
        </p>
      </article>
    </section>
  </div>
</Layout>
